<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1947-12-31T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1947-12-31T13:00:00-05:00" n="709" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d709">
                    <note rend="inline" type="source">125.288M/12–3147: Telegram</note>
                    <head>
                        <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss>
                            to the Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi></persName>)</head>
                    <opener>
                        <dateline rendition="#right">
                            <placeName>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1947-12-31T13:00:00-05:00">December 31,
                                1947—1 p. m.</date>
                        </dateline>
                    </opener>
                    <p>1586. Current situation in Manchuria, as described Changchun’s Tel 260 Dec
                            22<note n="2" xml:id="d709fn2">Not printed.</note> presumably rptd Emb,
                        and particularly increasing difficulty and hazardous communications leads
                        Dept seriously to question retention ConGen Changchun. Can this office be
                        closed and personnel withdrawn without fanfare since Dept wishes to avoid
                        adverse effect on ChiGovt’s position Manchuria.</p>
                    <closer>
                        <signed>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lovett</hi>
                        </signed>
                    </closer>
                </div>
                </body></text></TEI>